              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  A map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> being <fr:link href="/schm-BH0E/" title="Quasi-compact morphisms" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-BH0E/" display-uri="schm-BH0E" type="local">quasi-compact</fr:link> is an <fr:link href="/schm-WURZ/" title="Affine local on the target" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-WURZ/" display-uri="schm-WURZ" type="local">affine local property on the target</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  It suffices to show that if there is an affine open cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> that each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(\operatorname {Spec} A_i)]]></fr:tex> is quasi-compact, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is quasi-compact. This is trivial, since this implies that each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(\operatorname {Spec} A_i)]]></fr:tex> is covered by finitely many affine opens in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. 
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
